🔄 Study Phases — Which 5 Nodes to Power On 

Phase 1 — L2 Switching Foundation 

Nodes ON: SW1, SW2, SW3, PC1, PC2 

VLANs: Create VLANs 10, 20, 30 — assign access ports 

STP: Force SW1 as root bridge, observe port states, test RSTP convergence 

EtherChannel: Bundle SW1↔SW2 with LACP (mode active), verify with show etherchannel summary 

SPAN: Mirror SW2 traffic to PC1 for analysis (Switch Port Analyser) 

ACLs: Apply port-based ACLs on SW2 to restrict VLAN traffic 

 
 

Phase 2 — L3 Routing & OSPF Advanced 

Nodes ON: R1, R2, R3, SW1, PC1 

OSPF Multi-Area: R1=Area 0 (backbone), R2=Area 1, R3=Area 2 

OSPF Advanced: LSA types, route filtering with distribute-list, stub/NSSA areas 

Inter-VLAN routing: SW1 as L3 switch with SVIs, route to R2 

IP SLA: Configure ICMP echo tracking on R1 to monitor R2 reachability 

Static route tracking: Failover based on IP SLA results 

 
 

Phase 3 — BGP 

Nodes ON: R1, R2, R3, PC1, PC2 

eBGP: R1 simulates ISP, R2 and R3 are your AS 

iBGP: Full mesh between R2 and R3 

BGP attributes: Manipulate AS-PATH, LOCAL-PREF, MED, weight 

BGP filtering: Use prefix-lists and route-maps 

BGP communities: Tag and filter routes between peers 

 
 

Phase 4 — NAT, PAT, GLBP & IP Services 

Nodes ON: R1, R2, R3, PC1, PC2 

NAT/PAT: R1 translates inside (192.168.x.x) to simulated public IPs 

Static NAT: Map a specific inside host to a fixed public IP 

GLBP: R2 and R3 share a virtual gateway IP — test AVG/AVF roles, load balancing, and failover 

HSRP/VRRP comparison: Try all three FHRP protocols for comparison 

NTP: Set R1 as NTP master, sync R2/R3 

 
 

Phase 5 — Tunneling & Multicast 

Nodes ON: R1, R2, R3, PC1, PC2 

GRE Tunnel: Create a tunnel interface between R1 and R3 over R2's network 

IPsec over GRE: Add crypto map to the GRE tunnel 

DMVPN Phase 1: R1 as hub, R2/R3 as spokes 

Multicast: Enable PIM Sparse Mode, R2 as RP, verify with show ip mroute 

IGMP: PC1 joins a multicast group, verify membership 

 
 

Phase 6 — QoS & NetFlow 

Nodes ON: R1, R2, R3, PC1, PC2 

MQC (Modular QoS CLI): Define class-maps (DSCP, ACL-based), policy-maps, service-policies 

Traffic shaping vs policing: Apply on R1 WAN interface 

DSCP marking: Mark traffic at ingress on R2 

LLQ: Configure low-latency queue for voice-like traffic 

NetFlow (ETFlow): Enable ip flow ingress on R1/R2 interfaces, export to PC1 acting as collector 

 
 

Phase 7 — Automation & APIs 

Nodes ON: R1, R2, SW1, PC1, PC2 

RESTCONF/NETCONF: Enable on R1/R2 (restconf config), query from PC1 using curl or Python requests 

Python scripts on PC1: Automate VLAN creation via RESTCONF, pull interface stats via API 

Ansible (on PC1): Write a playbook to push config to R1 and SW1 

YANG models: Explore with show yang on IOS-XE nodes 

EEM (Embedded Event Manager): Script R1 to auto-log events or send syslog on interface down 

 
 

